T1  - Trends, random walks, and tests of the permanent income hypothesis
AU  - Gregory Mankiw, N.
AU  - Shapiro, Matthew D.
JO  - Journal of Monetary Economics
VL  - 16
IS  - 2
SP  - 165
EP  - 174
PY  - 1985
DA  - 1985/09/01/
SN  - 0304-3932
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-3932(85)90028-5
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304393285900285
AB  - Recent studies find that consumption is excessively sensitive to income. These studies assume that income is stationary around a deterministic trend. The data, however, do not reject the hypothesis that disposable personal income is a random walk with drift. If income is indeed a random walk, then the standard testing procedure is greatly biased toward finding excess sensitivity. Moreover, if income follows either a more general non-stationary process or a borderline stationary process, this procedure is also seriously biased.
